{"title_page": "Edward Grady Partin", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name=Edward Grady Partin, Sr.\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption= \n| birth_date={{birth date|1924|2|27}}\n| birth_place=[[Woodville, Mississippi]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|1990|3|11|1924|2|27}}\n| death_place = [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n| death_cause=[[Cardiovascular disease]] and [[diabetes]]\n| resting_place=Resthaven Gardens of Memory in Baton Rouge\n|occupation=[[Teamsters]] business agent\n|spouse=Divorced twice\n|children=7\n|alma_mater=\n|religion=\n|party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward Grady Partin, Sr.''' (February 27, 1924 &ndash; March 11, 1990), was an American business agent for the [[Teamsters Union]], best known for his 1964 testimony against [[Jimmy Hoffa]].<ref name=partin>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/13/obituaries/edward-partin-66-union-aide-became-anti-hoffa-witness.html|title=Edward Partin, 66; Union Aide Became Anti-Hoffa Witness|publisher=[[The New York Times]], March 12, 1990|accessdate=May 5, 2010 | date=March 13, 1990}}</ref>\n\n== Teamster Union and Mob Activities ==\nPartin was the manager of the Local 5 [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|IBT]] branch in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]] for 30 years.\n\nIn 1961, he was charged in the union with embezzlement as part of a stolen safe of union money. This would lead to the death of two key witnesses in the grand jury. He would be indicted on June 27, 1962 for 26 counts of embezzlement and falsification and released on bail. \n\nOn August 14, 1962 would be sued for his role in the wreck of a car injuring 2 and killing a third passenger. He would also be indicted for first-degree manslaughter and leaving the scene of an accident. He would then also surrender himself for aggravated kidnapping.\n\nIn the late 1960s, he would finally be convicted of conspiracy to obstruct justice through witness tampering and perjury in March 1979.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/13/obituaries/edward-partin-66-union-aide-became-anti-hoffa-witness.html|title=Edward Partin, 66; Union Aide Became Anti-Hoffa Witness|last=Ap|date=1990-03-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHe would then plead no-contest to numerous other corruption charges in the union, including embezzlement and would finally be released in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19700304&id=h58tAAAAIBAJ&sjid=U6AFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5983,2252438|title=Reading Eagle - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n== Testimony against Hoffa ==\nIn 1963, Jimmy Hoffa, the president of the Teamsters, was arrested for attempted jury tampering in attempted bribery of a grand juror of a previous 1962 case involving payments from a trucking company. Ed Partin testified that he was offered $20,000 to rig the jury in Hoffa's favor. The testimony would be the primary evidence of the Justice Department and would lead to him being sentenced to eight years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19700304&id=h58tAAAAIBAJ&sjid=U6AFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5983,2252438|title=Reading Eagle - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref> The entire case was rested on his testimony and he was considered the lone witness. \n\nPartin denied under oath that he was compensated by the Justice Department, but it was revealed that his ex-wife had her alimony payments given to her by the department. He originally denied that he would receive immunity or retroactive immunity for his testimony but it was later altered when he was under oath at a grand jury trial. \n<br />\n\n==See also==\n*[[J. Minos Simon]], a Partin attorney\n\n {{Portal|Biography|Mississippi|United States|Organized labor}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Partin, Edward Grady}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Woodville, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:International Brotherhood of Teamsters people]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:People associated with the assassination of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:American extortionists]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:People from McComb, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Democrats]]\n\n\n{{worker-activist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name=Edward Grady Partin, Sr.\n|image=\n|image_size=\n|caption= \n| birth_date={{birth date|1924|2|27}}\n| birth_place=[[Woodville, Mississippi]]\n| death_date={{death date and age|1990|3|11|1924|2|27}}\n| death_place = [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n| death_cause=[[Cardiovascular disease]] and [[diabetes]]\n| resting_place=Resthaven Gardens of Memory in Baton Rouge\n|occupation=[[Teamsters]] business agent\n|spouse=Divorced twice\n|children=7\n|alma_mater=\n|religion=\n|party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward Grady Partin, Sr.''' (February 27, 1924 &ndash; March 11, 1990), was an American business agent for the [[Teamsters Union]], best known for his 1964 testimony against [[Jimmy Hoffa]].<ref name=partin>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/13/obituaries/edward-partin-66-union-aide-became-anti-hoffa-witness.html|title=Edward Partin, 66; Union Aide Became Anti-Hoffa Witness|publisher=[[The New York Times]], March 12, 1990|accessdate=May 5, 2010 | date=March 13, 1990}}</ref>\n\n== Teamster Union and Mob Activities ==\nPartin was the manager of the Local 5 [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|IBT]] branch in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]] for 30 years.\n\nIn 1961, he was charged in the union with embezzlement as part of a stolen safe of union money. This would lead to the death of two key witnesses in the grand jury. He would be indicted on June 27, 1962 for 26 counts of embezzlement and falsification and released on bail. \n\nOn August 14, 1962 would be sued for his role in the wreck of a car injuring 2 and killing a third passenger. He would also be indicted for first-degree manslaughter and leaving the scene of an accident. He would then also surrender himself for aggravated kidnapping.\n\nIn the late 1960s, he would finally be convicted of conspiracy to obstruct justice through witness tampering and perjury in March of 1979.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/13/obituaries/edward-partin-66-union-aide-became-anti-hoffa-witness.html|title=Edward Partin, 66; Union Aide Became Anti-Hoffa Witness|last=Ap|date=1990-03-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-19|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHe would then plead no-contest to numerous other corruption charges in the union, including embezzlement and would finally be released in 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19700304&id=h58tAAAAIBAJ&sjid=U6AFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5983,2252438|title=Reading Eagle - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n== Testimony against Hoffa ==\nIn 1963, Jimmy Hoffa, the president of the Teamsters, was arrested for attempted jury tampering in attempted bribery of a grand juror of a previous 1962 case involving payments from a trucking company. Ed Partin testified that he was offered $20,000 to rig the jury in Hoffa's favor. The testimony would be the primary evidence of the Justice Department and would lead to him being sentenced to eight years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19700304&id=h58tAAAAIBAJ&sjid=U6AFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5983,2252438|title=Reading Eagle - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref> The entire case was rested on his testimony and he was considered the lone witness. \n\nPartin denied under oath that he was compensated by the Justice Department, but it was revealed that his ex-wife had her alimony payments given to her by the department. He originally denied that he would receive immunity or retroactive immunity for his testimony but it was later altered when he was under oath at a grand jury trial. \n<br />\n\n==See also==\n*[[J. Minos Simon]], a Partin attorney\n\n {{Portal|Biography|Mississippi|United States|Organized labor}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Partin, Edward Grady}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Woodville, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:International Brotherhood of Teamsters people]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n[[Category:People associated with the assassination of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:American extortionists]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:People from McComb, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Democrats]]\n\n\n{{worker-activist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTeamster Union and Mob Activities:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: March of 1979 \u2192 March 1979", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Grady_Partin"}
{"title_page": "Street fashion", "text_new": "{{merge from|Street Style|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Refimprove|article|date=April 2008}}\n[[File:Street fashion 2019 .jpg|thumb|[[Model (person)|Model]] in a modern look reflecting the current [[Street Style|street style]] fashion, [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], 2019. ]]\n'''Street fashion''' is [[fashion]] that is considered to have emerged not from studios, but from the grassroots [[streetwear]]. Street fashion is generally associated with [[youth culture]], and is most often seen in major urban centers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Urban Style and Tips|url=http://www.urbfash.com/2011/10/urban-style-and-tips.html|publisher=UrbFash}}</ref> Magazines and Newspapers like the [[New York Times]] and [[Elle magazine|Elle]] commonly feature candid photographs of individuals wearing urban, stylish clothing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cercone|first1=Katie|title=Today's Fashion|url=http://www.revoltmagazine.org/Issue_01/Articles/TODAYS_FASHION_article.htm|accessdate=20 November 2014|agency=Revolt Magazine|issue=Volume 1 Issue 1|publisher=Public Art Squad Project|date=2012|quote=Cindy Hinant, a visual artist whose daily trek through Soho makes her a regular target for amateur blogarazzi stalking women for photo copy, remarks, \"Street fashion has made me both paranoid and vain. Last week I had my photo taken twice in one day by two different magazines for their street fashion whatever. Now when I\u2019m wearing something that I think is awesome I\u2019m disappointed not to be stopped to have my picture taken.\"}}</ref>  [[Japanese street fashion]] sustains multiple simultaneous highly diverse fashion movements at any given time. Mainstream fashion often appropriates street fashion trends as influences. Nowadays, street fashion is getting more and more popular. Most major [[youth subculture]]s have had an associated street fashion. Examples from the [[1950s subcultures|1950s]], [[1970s subcultures|1970s]], [[1980s youth fashion|1980s]], [[1990s youth fashion|1990s]], [[2000s youth fashion|2000s]], and [[2010s youth fashion|2010s]] include:\n\n* [[Hippie]]s ([[denim]], bohemian style, long hair, flower power and psychedelic imagery, [[flared trousers]])\n* [[Teddy Boy]]s (drape jackets, drainpipe trousers, crepe shoes)\n* [[Punk fashion]] (ripped clothing, safety pins, bondage, provocative T-shirt slogans, Mohican hairstyle)\n* [[Skinhead]]s (short-cropped hair, fitted jeans, [[Ben Sherman]] button-up shirts, [[Fred Perry]] [[polo shirts]], [[Harrington jacket]]s, [[Dr. Martens]] boots)\n* [[Gothic fashion]] (black clothing, heavy coats, [[poet shirt]]s, big boots, makeup)\n* [[Preppy#Fashion|Preppy]] ([[Argyle (pattern)|argyle]] [[sweater]]s, [[chinos]], [[madras (cloth)|madras]], [[Nantucket Reds]], [[button down]] [[Oxford (cloth)|Oxford cloth]] shirts, and [[boat shoes]]). \n**See also [[ghetto prep]] for a 21st-century variant influenced by hip-hop fashion.\n* [[Hip hop fashion]] (ultra-baggy pants, ECKO, [[Tribal Gear]], [[Southpole (clothing)|South Pole]], Avirex, [[FUBU]], Sean Jean, [[Nike, Inc.|NIKE]])\n* [[Hipster (contemporary subculture)|Hipster]] or [[indie rock|indie]] ([[glasses]], [[jeans]], [[beanie (seamed cap)|beanie]]s, [[sneaker (footwear)|sneaker]]s, [[Necktie|ties]], [[suspenders]], checked shirts, [[beard]]s)\n* [[Trendies]] ([[Androgyny|androgynous]] [[big hair]], bright neon colors, [[skinny jeans]], printed hoodies, [[keffiyeh]]s)\n* [[Rastafari movement|Rasta]] ([[Clothing in Africa|African-inspired clothing]], [[rastacap]], [[dreadlocks]])\n* [[Greaser (subculture)]] (Levis 501 [[jeans]], [[T-shirts]], [[leather jackets]], [[sunglasses]], [[Cowboy boots]] or [[motorcycle boots]], [[hair gel]])\n* [[Urban culture|Urban]] (colorful apparel, large accent [[jewelry]], [[skinny jeans]], [[jackets]], [[T-shirt|T-shirts]])\n* Feminine ([[dresses]], [[hat]]s, [[sunglasses]], [[Handbag|hand bags]], floral prints)\n* [[Kawaii]] (tutu skirts, pastel and pink colors, [[anime]], childish and [[gothic lolita]] inspired accessories such as wild hair clips or bows)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bread and Butter tradeshow|Bread and Butter street fashion show]]\n* [[Purple Mark]]\n* [[Street Style]]\n* [[Streetwear]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Fashion}}\n{{Clothing}}\n\n[[Category:Street fashion| ]]\n\n\n{{fashion-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{merge from|Street Style|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Refimprove|article|date=April 2008}}\n[[File:Street fashion 2019 .jpg|thumb|[[Model (person)|Model]] in a modern look reflecting the current [[Street Style|street style]] fashion, [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], 2019. ]]\n'''Street fashion''' is [[fashion]] that is considered to have emerged not from studios, but from the grassroots [[streetwear]]. Street fashion is generally associated with [[youth culture]], and is most often seen in major urban centers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Urban Style and Tips|url=http://www.urbfash.com/2011/10/urban-style-and-tips.html|publisher=UrbFash}}</ref> Magazines and Newspapers like the [[New York Times]] and [[Elle magazine|Elle]] commonly feature candid photographs of individuals wearing urban, stylish clothing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cercone|first1=Katie|title=Today's Fashion|url=http://www.revoltmagazine.org/Issue_01/Articles/TODAYS_FASHION_article.htm|accessdate=20 November 2014|agency=Revolt Magazine|issue=Volume 1 Issue 1|publisher=Public Art Squad Project|date=2012|quote=Cindy Hinant, a visual artist whose daily trek through Soho makes her a regular target for amateur blogarazzi stalking women for photo copy, remarks, \"Street fashion has made me both paranoid and vain. Last week I had my photo taken twice in one day by two different magazines for their street fashion whatever. Now when I\u2019m wearing something that I think is awesome I\u2019m disappointed not to be stopped to have my picture taken.\"}}</ref>  [[Japanese street fashion]] sustains multiple simultaneous highly diverse fashion movements at any given time. Mainstream fashion often appropriates street fashion trends as influences. Most major [[youth subculture]]s have had an associated street fashion. Examples from the [[1950s subcultures|1950s]], [[1970s subcultures|1970s]], [[1980s youth fashion|1980s]], [[1990s youth fashion|1990s]], [[2000s youth fashion|2000s]], and [[2010s youth fashion|2010s]] include:\n\n* [[Hippie]]s ([[denim]], bohemian style, long hair, flower power and psychedelic imagery, [[flared trousers]])\n* [[Teddy Boy]]s (drape jackets, drainpipe trousers, crepe shoes)\n* [[Punk fashion]] (ripped clothing, safety pins, bondage, provocative T-shirt slogans, Mohican hairstyle)\n* [[Skinhead]]s (short-cropped hair, fitted jeans, [[Ben Sherman]] button-up shirts, [[Fred Perry]] [[polo shirts]], [[Harrington jacket]]s, [[Dr. Martens]] boots)\n* [[Gothic fashion]] (black clothing, heavy coats, [[poet shirt]]s, big boots, makeup)\n* [[Preppy#Fashion|Preppy]] ([[Argyle (pattern)|argyle]] [[sweater]]s, [[chinos]], [[madras (cloth)|madras]], [[Nantucket Reds]], [[button down]] [[Oxford (cloth)|Oxford cloth]] shirts, and [[boat shoes]]). \n**See also [[ghetto prep]] for a 21st-century variant influenced by hip-hop fashion.\n* [[Hip hop fashion]] (ultra-baggy pants, ECKO, [[Tribal Gear]], [[Southpole (clothing)|South Pole]], Avirex, [[FUBU]], Sean Jean, [[Nike, Inc.|NIKE]])\n* [[Hipster (contemporary subculture)|Hipster]] or [[indie rock|indie]] ([[glasses]], [[jeans]], [[beanie (seamed cap)|beanie]]s, [[sneaker (footwear)|sneaker]]s, [[Necktie|ties]], [[suspenders]], checked shirts, [[beard]]s)\n* [[Trendies]] ([[Androgyny|androgynous]] [[big hair]], bright neon colors, [[skinny jeans]], printed hoodies, [[keffiyeh]]s)\n* [[Rastafari movement|Rasta]] ([[Clothing in Africa|African-inspired clothing]], [[rastacap]], [[dreadlocks]])\n* [[Greaser (subculture)]] (Levis 501 [[jeans]], [[T-shirts]], [[leather jackets]], [[sunglasses]], [[Cowboy boots]] or [[motorcycle boots]], [[hair gel]])\n* [[Urban culture|Urban]] (colorful apparel, large accent [[jewelry]], [[skinny jeans]], [[jackets]], [[T-shirt|T-shirts]])\n* Feminine ([[dresses]], [[hat]]s, [[sunglasses]], [[Handbag|hand bags]], floral prints)\n* [[Kawaii]] (tutu skirts, pastel and pink colors, [[anime]], childish and [[gothic lolita]] inspired accessories such as wild hair clips or bows)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bread and Butter tradeshow|Bread and Butter street fashion show]]\n* [[Purple Mark]]\n* [[Street Style]]\n* [[Streetwear]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Fashion}}\n{{Clothing}}\n\n[[Category:Street fashion| ]]\n\n\n{{fashion-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Yhe7", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a sentence saying that street fashion is getting popular", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Street_fashion"}
{"title_page": "Peter Naholo", "text_new": "'''Peter Naholo''' is a [[Namibia]]n politician and former trade unionist. Naholo was a combatant with the [[People's Liberation Army of Namibia]] (PLAN), the military wing of the [[SWAPO]] liberation movement. In 2009, he was placed sixth on the National Assembly list for the newly formed [[Rally for Democracy and Progress (Namibia)|Rally for Democracy and Progress]] and earned a seat in the [[National Assembly of Namibia]]. On 14 September 2010, Naholo and 8 other opposition NA members were sworn in after boycotting the National Assembly due to electoral irregularities in the 2009 general election.<ref>[http://www.namibian.com.na/news/full-story/archive/2010/september/article/full-house/ Full house] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331214430/http://www.namibian.com.na/news/full-story/archive/2010/september/article/full-house/ |date=2012-03-31 }} [[The Namibian]], 15 September 2010</ref> On 19 October 2010, Naholo gave his first speech a member of the National Assembly; in that speech, Naholo asserted that some SWAPO politicians had enriched themselves through government since independence before being shouted down and asked to withdraw the accusation by Speaker [[Theo-Ben Gurirab]]. Later in the same session, several members of SWAPO accused Naholo and other RDP members of enriching themselves while in government as SWAPO members.<ref>[http://www.namibian.com.na/news/full-story/archive/2010/october/article/swapo-threatens-a-walkout-in-na/ Swapo threatens a walkout in NA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023071609/http://www.namibian.com.na/news/full-story/archive/2010/october/article/swapo-threatens-a-walkout-in-na |date=2010-10-23 }} [[The Namibian]], 20 October 2010</ref>\n\n==Trade Unions==\nNaholo was the Secretary General of the [[Mineworkers Union of Namibia]] from 1993\u20132001.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120903171504/http://www.newera.com.na/article.php?db=oldarchive&articleid=10306 Naholo on War Path] [[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]], 24 January 2006</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naholo, Peter}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n[[Category:Rally for Democracy and Progress (Namibia) politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Liberation Army of Namibia personnel]]\n[[Category:Members of SWAPO]]\n[[Category:Namibian trade unionists]]\n\n\n{{worker-activist-stub}}\n{{Namibia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Peter Naholo''' is a [[Namibia]]n politician and former trade unionist. Naholo was a combatant with the [[People's Liberation Army of Namibia]] (PLAN), the military wing of the [[SWAPO]] liberation movement. In 2009, he was placed sixth on the National Assembly list for the newly formed [[Rally for Democracy and Progress (Namibia)|Rally for Democracy and Progress]] and earned a seat in the [[National Assembly of Namibia]]. On 14 September 2010, Naholo and 8 other opposition NA members were sworn in after boycotting the National Assembly due to electoral irregularities in the 2009 general election.<ref>[http://www.namibian.com.na/news/full-story/archive/2010/september/article/full-house/ Full house] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331214430/http://www.namibian.com.na/news/full-story/archive/2010/september/article/full-house/ |date=2012-03-31 }} [[The Namibian]], 15 September 2010</ref> On 19 October 2010, Naholo gave his first speech a member of the National Assembly; in that speech, Naholo asserted that some SWAPO politicians had enriched themselves through government since independence before being shouted down and asked to withdraw the accusation by Speaker [[Theo-Ben Gurirab]]. Later in the same session, several members of SWAPO accused Naholo and other RDP members of enriching themselves while in government as SWAPO members.<ref>[http://www.namibian.com.na/news/full-story/archive/2010/october/article/swapo-threatens-a-walkout-in-na/ Swapo threatens a walkout in NA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023071609/http://www.namibian.com.na/news/full-story/archive/2010/october/article/swapo-threatens-a-walkout-in-na |date=2010-10-23 }} [[The Namibian]], 20 October 2010</ref>\n\n==Trade Unions==\nNaholo was the Secretary General of the [[Mineworkers Union of Namibia]] from 1993-2001.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120903171504/http://www.newera.com.na/article.php?db=oldarchive&articleid=10306 Naholo on War Path] [[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]], 24 January 2006</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Naholo, Peter}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Namibia)]]\n[[Category:Rally for Democracy and Progress (Namibia) politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Liberation Army of Namibia personnel]]\n[[Category:Members of SWAPO]]\n[[Category:Namibian trade unionists]]\n\n\n{{worker-activist-stub}}\n{{Namibia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrade Unions:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1993-2001 \u2192 1993\u20132001", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Naholo"}
